which succeeds in effacing the origins of the crop and the role of Africans and African-American slaves in transferring the seed, the cultivation skills, and the cultural practices necessary for establishing it in the New World. In this vivid interpretation of rice and slaves in the Atlantic world, Judith Carney reveals how racism has shaped our historical memory and neglected this critical African contribution to the making of the Americas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Apr 2021) 0aRicexHistoryxAfrica, West. 0aRicexHistoryxSouthern States. 0aRicezAfrica, WestxHistory. 0aRicezSouthern StatesxHistory. 0aSlavesxSouthern StatesxAfrica, WestxSouthern StatesxWestafrikaxUSAxSüdstaaten. 0aSlaveszSouthern States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674029217423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674029217.jpg  a978-3-11-044220-5  HUP eBook Package Backlist 2005-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK